## Complexity Analysis

| Complexity           | Value    |
| -------------------- | -------- |
| **Time Complexity**  | **O(n)** |
| **Space Complexity** | **O(h)** |

Where:

* **n** = Number of nodes in the tree.
* **h** = Height of the tree.

### Best Case (Balanced Tree)

```text
Space = O(log n)
```

### Worst Case (Skewed Tree)

```text
1
 \
  2
   \
    3
     \
      4
```

```text
Space = O(n)
```

---

## Why This Works

The solution follows the recursive definition of a tree's height:

> **The height of a node is one plus the maximum height of its left and right subtrees.**

Since each node computes its answer using the results from its children, the entire tree's maximum depth is calculated naturally.

Every node is visited exactly once, making this the optimal solution.

---

## Key Takeaways

* Uses **Depth First Search (DFS)** with recursion.
* Solves each subtree independently.
* Follows the recursive definition of tree height.
* Visits every node exactly once.
* Optimal **O(n)** time complexity.

